cyclone.name: ETA
cyclone.current_location: about 140 mi WSW of the Dry Tortugas and 125 mi N of the western tip of Cuba
cyclone.trajectory: Expected to slow, then turn north and meander over the southeastern Gulf before edging north-northeast toward the Florida Gulf Coast late Thursday–Friday; thereafter the remnant low moves across north-central Florida/Georgia and into the Atlantic.
cyclone.expected_landfall_location: Florida Big Bend coast (near Cedar Key–Steinhatchee area)

weather_observation.watch_coast: Tropical-storm watch in effect only for western Cuba (La Habana, Artemisa, Mayabeque, Pinar del Rio, Isle of Youth).
weather_observation.warning_coast: None at this time; interests along the Florida Gulf Coast advised to monitor.
weather_observation.impacted_coast: South-central and southwest Florida Peninsula and Keys for rain and gusty winds now; later this week the Florida Gulf Coast from Tampa Bay northward to the Big Bend likely to see direct impacts, with secondary effects extending across the peninsula toward the Atlantic beaches including Cape Canaveral.
weather_observation.wind: Breezy conditions with occasional gusts 25–35 mph possible late Wednesday through Friday as Eta crosses the state; less than a 1-in-5 chance of sustained tropical-storm-force winds.
weather_observation.storm_surge: None expected on the Cape Canaveral Atlantic side; any surge confined to Florida Gulf Coast.
weather_observation.rainfall: Bands could drop 1–3 inches with localized higher totals, producing brief ponding on terminals.
weather_observation.other_hazards: Elevated surf and dangerous rip currents along the Space Coast beginning mid-week.
